[normal]The British Government always bends over backwards to keep the European Commission happy even though 
[normal]the  
[normal]British Government
[normal], with taxpayers money, 
[normal]pays into the 
[normal]European Union more than the Government gets back.  Is it not time for the British Government to say that any changes to the CAP will in no way disadvantage British farmers even if the European Commission are not happy with that.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]With the population of hi
[normal]s country increasing rapidly it should be more important to ensure food production
[normal] for the majority of the people in this country, even to the extent of being self sufficient in some foods,
[normal] rather than environmental benefits
[normal] which benefit to the few.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]British farmers are well aware that this Government would like to do away with subsidies but would the general public be happy having to pay more for food.  The farmer may get a subsidy but in fact so do the general public as the subsidy keeps down the cos
[normal]t of food.  The Government should ask 
[normal]itself: do you want cheap food to help keep the cost of living down and so keep the general public happy or food production with no subsidy that forces food prices and the cost of living up.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8 October 2013
